To add support for setting form sequence for a workflow, we can modify the `Workflow` class to have a list of `Form` objects in the order they should appear in the workflow. We can add methods to add and remove `Form` objects from this list and to get the list of `Form` objects in the correct order.

Here's an updated implementation of the `Workflow` class with support for form sequence:
```typescript
public class Workflow {
    private String name;
    private List<Form> forms;

    public Workflow(String name) {
        this.name = name;
        forms = new ArrayList<>();
    }

    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }

    public void addForm(Form form) {
        forms.add(form);
    }

    public void removeForm(Form form) {
        forms.remove(form);
    }

    public List<Form> getForms() {
        // Return a copy of the list to prevent modification of the original list
        return new ArrayList<>(forms);
    }

    public List<Field> getAllFields() {
        List<Field> fields = new ArrayList<>();
        for (Form form : forms) {
            fields.addAll(form.getFields());
        }
        return fields;
    }

    public Form getFormById(int formId) {
        for (Form form : forms) {
            if (form.getId() == formId) {
                return form;
            }
        }
        return null;
    }

    public List<Submission> getSubmissions() {
        List<Submission> submissions = new ArrayList<>();
        for (Form form : forms) {
            submissions.addAll(form.getSubmissions());
        }
        return submissions;
    }

    public List<Submission> getSubmissionsByUser(User user) {
        List<Submission> submissions = new ArrayList<>();
        for (Form form : forms) {
            submissions.addAll(form.getSubmissionsByUser(user));
        }
        return submissions;
    }

    public List<Submission> getSubmissionsByStatus(SubmissionStatus status) {
        List<Submission> submissions = new ArrayList<>();
        for (Form form : forms) {
            submissions.addAll(form.getSubmissionsByStatus(status));
        }
        return submissions;
    }

    public List<Submission> getSubmissionsByUserAndStatus(User user, SubmissionStatus status) {
        List<Submission> submissions = new ArrayList<>();
        for (Form form : forms) {
            submissions.addAll(form.getSubmissionsByUserAndStatus(user, status));
        }
        return submissions;
    }

    public List<Submission> getSubmissionsByDateRange(Date startDate, Date endDate) {
        List<Submission> submissions = new ArrayList<>();
        for (Form form : forms) {
            submissions.addAll(form.getSubmissionsByDateRange(startDate, endDate));
        }
        return submissions;
    }

    public List<Submission> getSubmissionsByUserAndDateRange(User user, Date startDate, Date endDate) {
        List<Submission> submissions = new ArrayList<>();
        for (Form form : forms) {
            submissions.addAll(form.getSubmissionsByUserAndDateRange(user, startDate, endDate));
        }
        return submissions;
    }
}
```
We can then use this updated `Workflow` class to set the form sequence for a workflow by adding `Form` objects to the list in the desired order:
```java
Workflow workflow = new Workflow("Example Workflow");
Form form1 = new Form("Form 1");
Form form2 = new Form("Form 2");
Form form3 = new Form("Form 3");
workflow.addForm(form1);
workflow.addForm(form2);
workflow.addForm(form3);
```
